    theBad: "The detective narrative is intentionally convoluted and irresolvable, serving as a hazy framework for cultural nostalgia rather than a satisfying mystery puzzle.",
    review: "Inherent Vice is Thomas Pynchon's most accessible and affectionate novel — a stoner private-eye caper that infuses the hardboiled Chandleresque detective genre with marijuana haze, surf rock nostalgia, and profound paranoia at the tail end of the psychedelic sixties.\n\nSet in the fictional beach town of Gordita Beach, California, in late 1970 — just after the Manson family trial has permanently darkened the counterculture dream — the novel follows Larry 'Doc' Sportello, an perpetually stoned, benign private investigator. When Doc's femme fatale ex-girlfriend Shasta Fay Hepworth reappears pleading for help to foil a kidnapping plot against her new billionaire real estate lover Mickey Wolfmann, Doc stumbles into a labyrinthine underworld.\n\nDoc's investigation encounters an absurd cast of characters: the rigid, civil-rights-violating LAPD Detective 'Bigfoot' Bjornsen, surf rock saxophonists hiding from heroin syndicates, dentists specialized in money laundering, and the ominous Golden Fang — an entity that might be a global drug cartel, a tax shelter, or a phantom sailboat.\n\nBeneath the breezy, laugh-out-loud dialogue and slapstick comedy lies Pynchon's elegiac mourning for the utopian potential of the 1960s, crushed by authoritarian police powers and real estate greed. Inherent Vice is a delightful, sun-soaked farewell to American innocence.",
