    theBad: "Roth's intense, multi-page rhetorical monologues and unrelenting examination of societal breakdown can feel emotionally devastating and exhausting.",
    review: "American Pastoral is Philip Roth's supreme achievement and the first installment of his American Trilogy — a monumental, heartbreaking tragedy that interrogates the fragile illusion of postwar American prosperity and assimilation.\n\nNarrated by Roth's alter ego Nathan Zuckerman, the novel reconstructs the life of Seymour 'Swede' Levov, a legendary high school star athlete, former marine, and successful Jewish glove manufacturer. Married to a former Miss New Jersey and living in a beautiful stone farmhouse in Old Rimrock, the Swede embodies the triumphant assimilation of the American dream.\n\nThat dream is violently shattered in 1968 when his beloved teenage daughter, Merry, radicalized by the anti-Vietnam War movement, plants a bomb in the local post office that kills a respected town doctor. Merry goes into hiding, plunging the Swede into decades of agonizing self-examination as he tries to fathom how his home bred such destructive fury.\n\nThrough exuberant, sweeping prose, Roth contrasts the meticulous craft of glove manufacturing with the chaos of historical upheaval. American Pastoral is a profound masterpiece examining the inescapable impact of history on individual lives.",
