    theBad: "Its graphic, unrelenting depiction of masturbation, bodily functions, and neuroses can shock or offend readers unprepared for Roth's aggressive comedic transgressive style.",
    review: "Portnoy's Complaint arrived in 1969 like a cultural earthquake — a hilarious, scandalous, and revolutionary monologue that transformed American literature by liberating the depiction of sexual desire and guilt from moral restraint.\n\nThe entire novel takes the form of an impassioned confession delivered by 33-year-old Alexander Portnoy — the Assistant Commissioner of Human Opportunity for New York City — on the couch of his psychoanalyst, Dr. Spielvogel. Portnoy is torn between his high-minded ethical aspirations and his uncontrollable sexual lusts.\n\nRoth details Portnoy's suffocating upbringing under a fiercely overprotective Jewish mother and a constipated father, capturing the hilarious clash between familial obligation and individual appetite. Portnoy's desperate escapades with various women are recounted with unmatched comedic energy.\n\nBeneath the shock value and comedy lies a poignant exploration of identity, assimilation, and psychological paralysis. Portnoy's Complaint remains a fearless masterpiece of modern comic confessional fiction.",
