    theGood: "A fierce, brilliant indictment of 1990s political correctness and public hypocrisy — Roth unveils an extraordinary secret identity behind the downfall of a distinguished classics professor.",
    theBad: "Roth's scathing critique of ideological moralizing is delivered with an aggressive anger that occasionally overshadows the subtle character dynamics.",
    review: "The Human Stain is the powerhouse conclusion to Philip Roth's American Trilogy — an angry, brilliant investigation into public morality, political correctness, and the complex tragedy of American self-reinvention set against the backdrop of the 1998 Clinton-Lewinsky impeachment scandal.\n\nColeman Silk is a distinguished, aging classics professor and former dean at Athena College who is forced to resign after using the racial slur 'spooks' to refer to two chronically absent students who turn out to be African American. Retreating in disgrace, Silk begins an affair with Faunia Farley, an illiterate, traumatized campus janitor half his age.\n\nWhen Silk confides in narrator Nathan Zuckerman, the truth of his past is gradually revealed: Silk is actually a light-skinned African American man who chose to pass as white as a young man to achieve intellectual freedom in 1950s America. His secret sacrifice severed him from his family and identity.\n\nRoth masterfully connects Silk's personal tragedy to America's obsession with moral purity and public shaming. The Human Stain is a devastating, passionate literary achievement regarding the complexities of human identity.",
