    review: "Sabbath's Theater is Philip Roth's wild, raging masterpiece of mortality — a ferocious, Rabelaisian explosion of grief, lust, and defiance that centers on one of American fiction's most unforgettable reprobates.\n\n64-year-old Mickey Sabbath is a former street puppeteer whose arthritis has crippled his hands and whose life is falling apart following the sudden death of his beloved mistress, Drenka Balich. Driven mad by grief and facing impending death, Sabbath embarks on a self-destructive odyssey across New England.\n\nHe reconnects with old friends only to betray them, rummages through private belongings, confronts the ghosts of his vanished first wife and brother killed in World War II, and plots his own suicide with theatrical grandiosity.\n\nRoth writes with blazing vitality, matching Sabbath's vulgarity with philosophical depth. Sabbath's Theater is a courageous, heartbreaking exploration of the human body's betrayal and the raging desire to live.",
