    theGood: "A masterwork of alternate history — Roth plausibly imagines aviation hero and isolationist Charles Lindbergh defeating FDR in 1940, plunging American Jews into creeping fascist terror.",
    theBad: "The novel's abrupt historical resolution in the final chapters feels rushed compared to the meticulous, terrifying buildup of institutional anti-Semitism.",
    review: "The Plot Against America is Philip Roth's brilliant foray into alternate history — a gripping, terrifying novel that reimagines the vulnerability of American democracy during the outbreak of World War II.\n\nNarrated from the perspective of young Philip Roth growing up in Newark, New Jersey, the novel hypothesizes that aviation hero and vocal isolationist Charles A. Lindbergh wins the 1940 presidential election against Franklin D. Roosevelt. Signing a non-aggression pact with Adolf Hitler, President Lindbergh embarks on a program of normalization with Nazi Germany while initiating subtle state-sponsored anti-Semitism at home.\n\nRoth brilliantly captures how fascism takes root not overnight through armed coups, but gradually through bureaucratic programs like 'Just Folks,' which forcibly relocates Jewish boys to the Midwest to break familial cultural ties.\n\nAs the Roth family fracturing under pressure — with Philip's brother idolizing Lindbergh and his father stubbornly resisting — the atmosphere of dread thickens. The Plot Against America is an urgent, timeless reminder of the fragility of civil liberties.",
