    theBad: "Readers seeking sci-fi explanations or action-packed apocalyptic resolution will find instead a melancholic, character-driven domestic drama about unresolvable mourning.",
    review: "The Leftovers is Tom Perrotta's haunting meditation on universal grief — an apocalyptic novel that strips away the catastrophic spectacle of the disaster genre to focus intimately on the psychological aftermath of inexplicable loss.\n\nThree years ago, the 'Sudden Departure' occurred: exactly 2% of the world's population vanished simultaneously in an instant. It wasn't the biblical Rapture — saints vanished alongside sinners, leaving the remaining 98% stranded in a state of traumatized bewilderment without religious or scientific explanation.\n\nIn the suburban town of Mapleton, new police chief Kevin Garvey struggles to maintain normalcy as his own family disintegrates under the emotional weight. His wife, Laurie, has abandoned him to join the Guilty Remnant — a mute, white-robed cult dedicated to ensuring no one forgets the trauma. His son has joined a dubious prophet in the desert, while his daughter drifts into aimless nihilism.\n\nPerrotta writes with extraordinary empathy and understated realism, exploring how human beings construct coping mechanisms when certainty vanishes. The Leftovers is a poignant, beautifully observed masterpiece about living with unresolvable sorrow.",
