    theBad: "Brief episodic vignettes mean some compelling historical eras are exited before full immersion.",
    review: "Emily St. John Mandel's Sea of Tranquility (2022) is a breathtaking specimen of speculative fiction that weaves together science fiction tropes—time travel, lunar colonies, and the simulation hypothesis—into a deeply human meditation on art, grief, and historical recurrence. Spanning five centuries, the novel connects an exiled British aristocrat in the 1912 Canadian wilderness, a writer on a book tour on Earth during a pandemic in 2203, and a detective living in Moon Colony City 275 in 2401.\n\nThe connecting thread across these centuries is an anomaly: a strange, overlapping sensory experience where characters hear the notes of a violin playing in an airship terminal alongside the sounds of a forest disturbance. Detective Gaspery-Jacques Roberts is tasked by the Time Institute to investigate whether this anomaly proves that the universe is a computational simulation.\n\nDespite its vast cosmic scope, Mandel keeps the narrative anchored in intimate, emotional specificity. The novel reflects profoundly on the collective trauma of COVID-19 through the lens of interstellar distance, ultimately suggesting that even if our reality is a simulation, the love, beauty, and kindness we generate within it remain entirely real and meaningful.",
