    review: "In Black Swan Green (2006), David Mitchell sets aside his trademark complex structural acrobatics and globetrotting fantasy to deliver a semi-autobiographical, deeply sensitive coming-of-age masterpiece. Set over thirteen months in 1982 in a sleepy Worcestershire village, the novel chronicles the thirteenth year of Jason Taylor, a closeted poet who secretly battles a debilitating stammer he personifies as 'Hangman.'\n\nAgainst the backdrop of the Falklands War, Thatcherite austerity, and his parents' disintegrating marriage, Jason navigates the treacherous, hyper-masculine social hierarchy of teenage boyhood—where showing vulnerability or artistic sensitivity is social suicide. Mitchell captures the excruciating self-consciousness, cruel bullies, and linguistic obsessions of youth with uncanny, flawless psychological precision.\n\nEach of the thirteen chapters functions as a standalone short story centered on a specific adventure or crisis—from smoking cigarettes in secret woods to encountering an eccentric European emigre (Madame Crommelynck from Cloud Atlas) who mentors his poetry. Black Swan Green is a funny, heartbreaking, and universally resonant triumph of voice and empathy.",
